{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658220"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:44:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:44:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20718"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20718"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13594"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96084"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13594"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20718"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78816"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11587"},{"type":"tags","id":"11762"},{"type":"tags","id":"12581"},{"type":"tags","id":"12597"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32686"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32687"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96084"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents with a two-day history of small, non-blanching red spots on her lower legs. She also reports having had two nosebleeds in the past week and heavier than usual menstrual bleeding. Physical examination reveals multiple pinpoint haemorrhages (1-2 mm) scattered across her shins and ankles. Laboratory tests show a platelet count of 15 \u00d7 10^9/L (150-400).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best explains the pathophysiology of the patient\u0027s skin findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Antibody-mediated destruction of erythrocytes","Excessive fibrinolysis dissolving clots","Failure of platelet adhesion to damaged endothelium","Vasculitis causing inflammation of blood vessels","Deficiency of vitamin K-dependent clotting factors"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has petechiae (pinpoint haemorrhages 1-2 mm in size) due to severe thrombocytopenia. The pathophysiology involves \u003Cstrong\u003Efailure of platelet adhesion to damaged endothelium\u003C/strong\u003E. Normally, platelets rapidly seal minor defects in capillaries that occur from everyday minor trauma, particularly in skin and mucosal surfaces. With insufficient platelets, these minor capillary ruptures cannot be sealed, resulting in petechial haemorrhages.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcessive fibrinolysis dissolving clots\u003C/strong\u003E - While this can cause bleeding, it typically results in larger haemorrhages rather than petechiae and would affect formed clots rather than prevent initial platelet adhesion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeficiency of vitamin K-dependent clotting factors\u003C/strong\u003E - This represents a defect in secondary haemostasis (coagulation cascade) rather than primary haemostasis, and typically causes larger, deeper bleeds rather than petechiae\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntibody-mediated destruction of erythrocytes\u003C/strong\u003E - This would cause haemolytic anaemia rather than bleeding manifestations\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasculitis causing inflammation of blood vessels\u003C/strong\u003E - While vasculitis can cause purpuric lesions, the patient\u0027s presentation with thrombocytopenia and mucosal bleeding is more consistent with a primary haemostasis defect\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s presentation with petechiae, mucosal bleeding (epistaxis), and menorrhagia is classic for a primary haemostasis defect, in this case severe thrombocytopenia with a platelet count of 15 \u00d7 10^9/L. Intracerebral haemorrhage is a feared complication of severe thrombocytopenia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Defects in primary haemostasis (platelet defects or von Willebrand disease) typically present with petechiae and purpura in skin and mucosal membranes.","Petechiae are minute haemorrhages (1-2 mm) that occur when platelets fail to seal capillary defects following minor trauma.","Thrombocytopenia can lead to serious complications including intracerebral haemorrhage.","Mucosal bleeding manifestations of primary haemostasis defects include epistaxis, gastrointestinal bleeding, and menorrhagia."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 4; page 125."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78816"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20718"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78816"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-30T22:36:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-30T22:37:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13594"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96084"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11587"},"attributes":{"emoji":